  "answer": "Comte's argument (Traité de la propriété Vol. I, ch. 1) is specifically about how Roman/Greek jurisprudence was distorted by the institution of chattel slavery: jurists like Papinian, Paul, and Ulpian were slave-owners who could not ground rights and duties in human nature without contradicting their practice. They therefore had to build legal foundations on principles they could not demonstrate, leaving jurisprudence permanently compromised. Comte frames this as a philosophical-theoretical problem — a contradiction between professed natural liberty (jus naturale) and the practice of treating persons as property — that contaminates all subsequent legal thinking that inherits Roman doctrine.\n\nThe smriti tradition, by contrast, provides an elaborate internal jurisprudence of dāsa rather than a critique of it. The Nāradasmṛti (ch. 1, Nar. 5.02–5.42) identifies fifteen categories of dāsa, differentiated by mode of entry: born in the house, purchased, received as gift, inherited, maintained during a famine, pledged by master, freed from great debt, captured in battle, won in a wager, self-submitted, apostate from asceticism, time-limited, slave for food, enslaved for a female slave, and self-sold. Crucially, each category has distinct exit conditions: hereditary slaves (first four) are released only by master's grace or by saving the master's life; debt-slaves are released on repayment; battle-captives on providing a substitute; and Nar. 5.36 explicitly declares that those 'abducted by thieves and sold, and those enslaved by force — they must be freed by the king; slavery is not intended for them.' The Manusmṛti (ch. 8, Mn. 8.413–8.415) lists seven categories and adds a structurally distinct claim: the Shudra is a natural servant whose servitude is innate and cannot be removed even by manumission.\n\nAre they describing the same phenomenon at different distances, or different phenomena under one English word?\n\nThe answer is primarily: different phenomena, with a zone of overlap. Several diagnostics:\n\n1. Forced enslavement: Nar. 5.36's declaration that forced enslavement is illegitimate and must be undone by the king is irreconcilable with Roman law's acceptance of war captives as slaves — one of the central sources Comte identifies. The most morally contested category in Rome is actively delegitimized in the Nāradasmṛti.\n\n2. Caste-as-servitude: Manu's claim that a Shudra cannot be freed from servitude because it is 'innate' (Mn. 8.414) describes something Roman law has no counterpart for — a cosmic-order-based permanent condition that precedes and survives any contractual or conquest-based legal status. This is not slavery in Comte's sense (legally acquired property in a person) but a dharmic category that English translates as servitude for lack of a better word.\n\n3. Temporal and conditional forms: The smriti system has many time-limited and condition-based forms (debt-slave released on payment, famine-slave released by two oxen, food-slave released by master's failure to provide food). These are closer to indentured servitude or debt peonage than to the Roman chattel model Comte analyzes.\n\n4. The distortion argument: Comte's critique targets the specific contradiction in Roman jurisprudence between professing natural liberty as the foundation of rights while denying it to slaves. The smriti tradition does not have this contradiction — it does not claim natural liberty as a universal baseline. It builds a hierarchical cosmic order in which different beings have different prescribed roles. There is therefore no distortion of the kind Comte identifies: the smriti is internally consistent in its own terms, even if its terms are inegalitarian.\n\nZone of genuine overlap: The four permanent hereditary categories in Nārada (born in house, purchased, received as gift, inherited — Nar. 5.24, 5.27) are structurally close to Roman chattel slavery. For this subset, Comte's analysis does apply: a jurisprudence built around persons-as-inheritable-property faces the same foundational contradiction. This is the narrow sense in which they describe the same phenomenon.\n\nConclusion: The smriti dāsa system and Comte's ancient slavery are not the same phenomenon at different distances. The smriti term dāsa covers a spectrum from hereditary chattel (overlapping with Comte's target) to debt peonage to cosmic-order-based Shudra service — categories English collapses under 'slave' or 'servant' but which have distinct legal logics. Comte's critique of jurisprudential distortion applies most directly to the hereditary/purchased subset within the smriti scheme, but is structurally deflected by the smriti's dharmic framing, which avoids the natural-liberty contradiction by never claiming universal natural liberty in the first place.",
